http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title.value: Rhode Island K-12 Grade Span Expectations in Engineering and Technology

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: This document, the Rhode Island K-12 Grade Span Expectations (GSEs) in Engineering and Technology, has been developed as a means to identify the concepts and skills necessary to foster literacy in Engineering and Technology expected of all students. The GSEs provide direction for in-depth learning and application of skills that will be required to meet the challenges of a future that is increasingly dependent upon a STEM literate workforce.
Engineering and technology impacts the world and humankind.
Demonstrate and identify reasons for the development of technology and its effects on humankind.
Students demonstrate an understanding of the nature of technology by:
investigating life without current technology (e.g. role-play use of the bucket brigade instead of a fire truck)
describing how technology affects daily human routines (e.g. How does milk get from the cow to the home refrigerator?)
differentiating between needs/wants, helpful/harmful, disposable/reusable, and natural/human-made products.
Students demonstrate an understanding of the nature of technology by:
comparing and contrasting life with and without current technology and how technology impacts everyday life.
recognizing that technology has positive and negative outcomes utilizing specific examples.
identifying natural (e.g. wood, fur, stone) vs. human-made objects (e.g. plastic, Styrofoam)
Compare, contrast, and provide evidence of how technology influences history and impacts society.
Students demonstrate an understanding of the impact of technology by:
researching and displaying how technological advancements have inspired historical events (e.g. Cold War/Sputnik, slavery/ cotton gin)
listing and describing the importance of technology in daily life and its trade-offs
evaluating the many and varying uses of technology within different geographic regions (e.g. geothermal, tidal, and wind power
Students demonstrate an understanding of the impact of technology by:
describing how technological advances affect society (e.g. horse drawn carriages to automobiles)
comparing and contrasting the social and economic concerns that arise for the individual, the family, and/or the community as a result of technological advancements
analyzing the use of technology within various cultures (e.g. Amish, Japanese
Identify the factors affecting technological advances (e.g. social, economic, political, cultural, and environmental) throughout history.
Students demonstrate an understanding of the influences of technology by:
analyzing factors related to the development of technology and its effects on the rate of change on the designed world.
assessing the relationship between available resources and the development of technology.
analyzing the evolution of factors affecting technological advances in a global environment (e.g. satellites, transportation, media).
forecasting technological advancements based on potential needs and wants. (e.g. eBooks, Kindle)
developing technology to meet a need and identify potential tradeoffs.
Discuss and develop an understanding of technology and its relationship to the natural and designed (human-made) world in the local community.
Students demonstrate an understanding of the need for technology by:
understanding that technology can make life easier (e.g. clothes, telephone, automobile, microwave).
discussing the purpose of technology and its relationship to the natural and designed world
Students demonstrate an understanding of the need for technology by:
understanding that technology is any process or invention that affects society (e.g. impact of the tractor on farming, indoor plumbing).
discussing the purpose of technology and how it has affected humankind. (e.g. interview people from different generations to compare changes in lifestyles due to technological advancements).
Describe and demonstrate the effects of technological systems on humankind in terms of a national scale.
Students demonstrate an understanding of the outcomes of technology by:
making connections between technological inventions and their impacts on a nation. (e.g. automobiles and highway systems; computerized machines and manufacturing).
researching and analyzing the effects on humankind and the environment that a particular technology has had over a period of time (e.g. landfill, dam on a river, desalinization plant).
Students demonstrate an understanding of the outcomes of technology by:
designing a technological product and explaining how it may impact society. (e.g. television, cell phones, jumbo jets, water purification systems)
associating and illustrating the effects of particular technological systems over a period of time (e.g. waste disposal systems, potable water systems)
Analyze and explain advancements in technological systems and their impact on the world.
Students demonstrate an understanding of the impacts of technology by:
revising a current technological system and analyzing the global effects of the innovation (e.g. transition from fossil fuels to use of renewable resources).
modeling the design of a technological system and evaluating its impact on humankind
designing a technological system to meet a specified need and analyzing its potential impact on the world
Effective design through engineering and technology is the outcome of a problem solving process involving the application of content knowledge, acquired skills, and creativity.
Explore and recognize the attributes of a design process.
Students demonstrate an understanding of the attributes of a design process by:
asking questions, making observations, and brainstorming various ideas.
exploring solutions to a problem based upon observations and brainstorming ideas.
completing tasks cooperatively in a group setting.
Students demonstrate an understanding of the attributes of a design process by:
defining a problem and expressing design ideas for that problem to others.
solving problems through the creation of design solutions.
identifying the characteristics of being an effective team member and working together to complete a task.
Utilize the attributes of a design process to solve a real world problem.
Students demonstrate an understanding of the attributes of a design process by:
defining a problem that addresses a scenario with given criteria and constraints.
selecting an appropriate design solution for a given scenario or task.
fulfilling a specific function as a team member to achieve a desired result.
Students demonstrate an understanding of the attributes of a design process by:
defining a problem that addresses a scenario by identifying its criteria and constraints.
selecting and justifying an appropriate design solution for a given scenario or task.
explaining what makes an effective design team and working together to achieve a desired result.
Evaluate and refine the design used to solve a real world problem.
Students demonstrate an understanding of the attributes of a design process by:
identifying in-depth criteria and constraints by developing a concise problem statement.
evaluating and finalizing the most appropriate design solution for a given scenario or task
creating a team and assigning roles to team members for the purpose of achieving an overall desired result.
reevaluating the process utilized in the development of the design solution with the goal of enhanced efficiency.
identifying the personnel positions required to complete a task and the essential qualities required of each position
Explore and recognize basic technological products and systems, as well as their tools.
Students demonstrate an understanding of technological products and systems by:
identifying and safely using the required tools (e.g. glue, scissors, tape) for a specific task.
collecting and using information about everyday products and symbols. (e.g. shape and color of a stop sign)
exploring how things work.
exploring the properties of a product (e.g. size, type of material, shape).
Students demonstrate an understanding of technological products and systems by:
identifying and safely using the required tools (e.g. glue, scissors, tape) and information resources for a specific task.
using information to identify patterns within those systems.
following step by step procedures and identifying sequential actions.
identifying the effects of technology and comparing and contrasting tradeoffs (e.g. advantage of using scissors vs. paper cutter or tearing paper).
Use and maintain technological products and systems, as well as their tools.
Students demonstrate an understanding of technological products and systems by:
safely using the required tools and organizing information resources for a specific task.
incorporating assigned materials and assigned tools throughout the design process.
using information to discover, diagnose and troubleshoot problems that arise in the course of the design process.
interpreting the accuracy of information for the purpose of developing possible solutions.
Students demonstrate an understanding of technological products and systems by:
safely using the required tools and organizing and explaining information resources for a specific task.
incorporating information, proper materials and tool selection throughout the design process.
using tools to diagnose, adjust, and repair problems that arise in the course of the design process.
interpreting and evaluating the accuracy of information for the purpose of developing possible solutions.
Incorporate technological products, systems and their tools to achieve design solutions.
Students demonstrate an understanding of technological products and systems by:
selecting independently the proper tools or information resources used in completing a task.
incorporating proper information, material selection and appropriate tools throughout the design process. (e.g. digital micrometers, digital oscilloscopes)
documenting, communicating, and evaluating processes and procedures used to build, operate, and maintain systems.
integrating information to develop possible solutions and evaluate designs.
designing specific tools (e.g. jigs and fixtures) to expedite the task.
creating technically written documentation to support a designed product.
Explore the processes of research and development, invention and innovation, experimentation, and troubleshooting in planning practical solutions to problems.
Students demonstrate an understanding of effective design by:
recognizing there are steps to solving a problem.
experimenting / exploring with various simple machines (e.g. wheels, axles, gears, pulleys) to demonstrate their uses and discuss their differences.
asking questions and making observations of design solutions (e.g. comparing toothbrush designs).
comparing and contrasting various design solutions (e.g. bus vs. race car).
Students demonstrate an understanding of effective design by:
exploring a process to solve a real world problem.

using age-appropriate construction materials based on specific properties (e.g. strength, hardness, flexibility) and tools (e.g. pliers, tape measure, hammer, nails) to build a model to solve a specific problem.
testing, troubleshooting, and evaluating a basic design solution.
documenting the advantages and disadvantages of multiple designs (e.g. various designs of can openers).
Utilize processes (i.e. research and development, invention and innovation, experimentation, and troubleshooting) in designs that use criteria and constraints leading to useful products and systems.
Students demonstrate an understanding of effective designs of products and systems by:
given a process, with criteria and constraints, solve a real world problem.
utilizing materials provided to construct a working model for a given task (e.g. construct a contraption that utilizes all the simple machines – chain reaction machine).
testing, troubleshooting, and evaluating a design solution.
presenting final working model for peer review and revision.
Students demonstrate an understanding of effective designs of products and systems by:
independently develop and utilize a process to solve a real world problem.
presenting documentation, revisions, and final working model to their peers using a variety of technological tools.
Refine the processes of research and development, invention and innovation, experimentation, and troubleshooting for the purpose of achieving an optimal design solution.
Students demonstrate an understanding of what is an optimal design solution by:
independently develop and utilize a process to solve a real world problem and justifying the selection.
selecting appropriate materials to construct a working prototype and/or simulation.
evaluating and refining a complex design solution for a working prototype
presenting comparative simulations/ prototypes and defending the selected solution.
revising a process to solve a real world problem given unexpected constraints. (e.g. time, funding, personnel)
developing an alternative solution to a design problem.
researching the patent application process.
presenting solutions to a community problem in a public forum (e.g. senior exhibitions).
The designed world community selects and uses appropriate technologies.
Recognize that there are various areas in engineering and technology.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: The Areas of Engineering and Technology as identified by the International Technology Engineering and Education Association are: Medical, Agricultural and Biotechnologies, Energy and Power, Information and Communication, Transportation, Manufacturing, and Construction.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Students demonstrate an understanding of the areas of engineering and technology by:
identifying community workers in the areas of engineering and technology. (e.g. bus driver in the area of transportation)
making connections between the different areas of engineering and technology (e.g. recognize that transportation technologies are involved in construction).
Students demonstrate an understanding of the areas of engineering and technology by:
identifying responsibilities of community workers in the areas of engineering and technology.
specifying and explaining the connections within the areas of engineering and technology.
Explore the various areas in engineering and technology and their interconnections.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: The Areas of Engineering and Technology as identified by the International Technology Engineering and Education Association are: Medical, Agricultural and Biotechnologies, Energy and Power, Information and Communication, Transportation, Manufacturing, and Construction.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Students demonstrate an understanding of the areas of engineering and technology by:
differentiating among the various engineering and technological careers (e.g. medical technologist vs. biotechnologist).
researching the connections within the areas of engineering and technology as they apply to a given product.
Students demonstrate an understanding of the areas of engineering and technology by:
researching and defining the requirements of a particular engineering / technological discipline.
evaluating the connections within the areas of engineering and technology as they apply to an assigned product.
Experience and implement the various areas in engineering and technology.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: The Areas of Engineering and Technology as identified by the International Technology Engineering and Education Association are: Medical, Agricultural and Biotechnologies, Energy and Power, Information and Communication, Transportation, Manufacturing, and Construction.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Students demonstrate an understanding of the areas of engineering and technology by
preparing a career portfolio of a particular area of engineering or technology.
evaluating the connections within the areas of engineering and technology as they apply to a student designed product.
participating in an internship or job shadowing opportunity in a particular engineering / technological discipline.
Select and utilize appropriate tools to measure, design, and implement specific technologies.
Students demonstrate an understanding of selecting appropriate tools by:
recognizing that there are specialized tools for different areas of engineering and technology.
Students demonstrate an understanding of selecting appropriate tools by:
identifying characteristics of appropriate tools within different technologies.
experimenting and selecting the optimal tool for a given task in a specific area of technology.
Compare and contrast tools to measure, design, and implement specific technologies.
Students demonstrate an understanding of selecting appropriate tools by:
comparing and contrasting tools used for the same purpose across different technologies (e.g. linear measurement tools in construction vs. digital measurement tools in biotechnology).
researching and selecting the optimal tool for a given task in a specific area of technology.
Students demonstrate an understanding of selecting appropriate tools by:
researching and explaining the evolution of key tool(s) used in specific technologies (e.g. the evolution of the microscope in the medical area).
researching and selecting the optimal tool for a student-selected task in a specific area of technology.
Evaluate the effectiveness of tools to measure, design, and implement specific technologies.
Students demonstrate an understanding of selecting appropriate tools by:
evaluating the effectiveness of various tool(s) used in specific technologies.
developing or improving a tool for a specific technology (e.g. software, jig, fixture).
Design, manufacture and test a prototype.
